					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/veggiekeks" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1814651); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1814651&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610163898" alt="Veggiekeks" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1814651)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/veggiekeks" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1814651); return false;" >Veggiekeks</a></span> <span class="odate time_1391775223 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">07 Feb 2014 12:13</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-1959748">
									

<p>I think virtue ehtics isn't that common now for some good reasons. Quickly summed up, because it is weird (that of course being only my perception). Also try applying it to Foundation moral: While this would sure be worth some laughs, I doubt the Foundation could justify much with it mainly because the Foundations virtues aren't the best to build moral up on them.</p>
<p>While the other problems you mention sure are present, one can dicuss them only when already decided between deontology and consequentialism.<br />
Therefore I think as long Foundation ethcics on grand scale are the topic one can't avoid the consequentialism vs. deontology debate. When writing about some special topic inside Foundation ehtics it may be possible to apply some other ethical perspectives.</p>

							</div>

								
					
